James Edward Heath (October 25, 1926 â€“ January 19, 2020), nicknamed Little Bird, was an American jazz saxophonist, composer, arranger, and big band leader.
Heath was born in Philadelphia on October 25, 1926.
In 1946, he formed his own band, which was a fixture on the Philadelphia jazz scene until 1949.
The band performed at venues such as the Apollo Theater in Harlem.
The band performed at venues such as the Apollo Theater in Harlem.
Although Heath recalls that the band recorded a few demos on acetate, it never released any recordings, and its arrangements were lost at a Chicago train station.

After release, In early 1955, still an addict, he was arrested again, and served most of a six-year prison sentence in Lewisburg.
In the 1980s, Heath joined the faculty of the Aaron Copland School of Music at Queens College, City University of New York.
He also served on the Board of the Louis Armstrong Archives on campus, and the restoration and management of the Louis and Lucille Armstrong Residence in Corona, Queens, near his own home.
At a coming-home party the night after his release from Lewisburg Penitentiary, he met his eventual wife, Mona Brown, whom he married in 1960; they had two children, Roslyn and Jeffrey.
